#data

data <- read.csv("C:/Users/rakib/Desktop/Thesis/DATA/combined final data set/final_data.csv")

data <- data%>%
  select(-c(date, fips_code))

#RFE

# Define predictors (make sure to exclude target + IDs)
predictor_cols <- setdiff(names(data), c("total_outage", "county", 'event_name'))

set.seed(1000)
# Control setup
ctrl <- rfeControl(functions = rfFuncs, # use random forest functions
                   method = "cv",       # cross-validation
                   number = 5)          # 5-fold CV


# Run RFE
rfe_model <- rfe(
  x = data[, predictor_cols],
  y = data$total_outage,
  sizes = c(16, 18, 20, 22, 23),         # test different feature set sizes
  rfeControl = ctrl
)

#best subset
predictors(rfe_model)
##  [1] "prev_outage"                   "prev_3day_avg_outage"         
##  [3] "max_prcp"                      "mean_prcp"                    
##  [5] "day_difference"                "max_wind_gust_kts"            
##  [7] "max_wind_speed_kts"            "avg_wind_speed_kts"           
##  [9] "min_temp_f"                    "min_prcp"                     
## [11] "central_pressure"              "mean_min_ndvi"                
## [13] "avg_rh"                        "mean_mean_ndvi"               
## [15] "max_rh"                        "max_temp_f"                   
## [17] "developed_and_other_human_use" "density_mi2"
#Plot Performance vs. Number of Features
plot(rfe_model, type = c("g", "o"))

#data split and selected variables

#selected variables
selected_vars <- predictors(rfe_model)
set.seed(1)
# Split data into 80% training and 20% testing
train_index <- createDataPartition(data$total_outage, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train_data <- data[train_index, ]
test_data <- data[-train_index, ]

Random Forest

#Tune mtry with Cross-Validation
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5)

tune_grid <- expand.grid(
  mtry = c(4, 6, 8, 10, 12)
)
set.seed(1001)
tuned_rf <- train(
  x = train_data[, selected_vars],
  y = train_data$total_outage,
  method = "rf",
  tuneGrid = tune_grid,
  trControl = ctrl
)
print(tuned_rf)
## Random Forest 
## 
## 4636 samples
##   18 predictor
## 
## No pre-processing
## Resampling: Cross-Validated (5 fold) 
## Summary of sample sizes: 3709, 3710, 3708, 3709, 3708 
## Resampling results across tuning parameters:
## 
##   mtry  RMSE      Rsquared   MAE     
##    4    129702.4  0.6933692  16756.49
##    6    126627.5  0.6992991  15736.26
##    8    124205.9  0.7082875  15395.33
##   10    123103.2  0.7050777  15041.91
##   12    123906.4  0.7012425  14982.09
## 
## RMSE was used to select the optimal model using the smallest value.
## The final value used for the model was mtry = 10.
best_mtry <- tuned_rf$bestTune$mtry
cat("Best mtry:", best_mtry, "\n")
## Best mtry: 10
plot(tuned_rf)

#variable imp
varImp(tuned_rf, scale = FALSE)
## rf variable importance
## 
##                                 Overall
## prev_outage                   1.172e+14
## prev_3day_avg_outage          3.983e+13
## max_prcp                      1.792e+13
## mean_prcp                     1.640e+13
## max_rh                        7.962e+12
## max_wind_gust_kts             6.808e+12
## avg_wind_speed_kts            6.037e+12
## max_wind_speed_kts            5.159e+12
## day_difference                4.627e+12
## avg_rh                        3.834e+12
## min_temp_f                    3.363e+12
## max_temp_f                    3.250e+12
## mean_min_ndvi                 2.650e+12
## min_prcp                      2.447e+12
## density_mi2                   2.076e+12
## developed_and_other_human_use 1.964e+12
## central_pressure              1.891e+12
## mean_mean_ndvi                1.033e+12
plot(varImp(tuned_rf, scale = FALSE))

#predict on test data
preds <- predict(tuned_rf, newdata = test_data[, selected_vars])
preds[preds < 0] <- 0
actuals <- test_data$total_outage
# Evaluate
results <- postResample(pred = preds, obs = actuals)

# Format results as a data frame
eval_table <- data.frame(
  Metric = c("RMSE", "R-squared", "MAE"),
  Value = c(
    round(results["RMSE"], 4),
    round(results["Rsquared"], 4),
    round(results["MAE"], 4)
  )
)

# Print table
print(eval_table)
##             Metric      Value
## RMSE          RMSE 99477.8739
## Rsquared R-squared     0.9039
## MAE            MAE 12396.6467
#Traditional/Definition based R2
sst <- sum((actuals - mean(actuals))^2)
sse <- sum((actuals - preds)^2)
r2_traditional <- 1 - (sse / sst)
cat("Traditional R-squared:", round(r2_traditional, 4))
## Traditional R-squared: 0.8476
#actual vs prediction plot
plot_df <- data.frame(
  actuals = actuals,
  preds = preds
)
ideal_line_df <- data.frame(x = c(0, max(plot_df$actuals)), y = c(0, max(plot_df$actuals)))
ggplot(plot_df, aes(x = actuals, y = preds)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = "Actual vs Predicted Points")) +
  geom_smooth(aes(color = "Regression Line"), method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
   geom_line(data = ideal_line_df, aes(x = x, y = y, color = "Ideal Line"), linetype = "dashed", size = 1) +
  scale_color_manual(
    name = "Legend",
    values = c(
      "Actual vs Predicted Points" = "blue",
      "Regression Line" = "green",
      "Ideal Line" = "red"
    )
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = label_comma()) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = label_comma()) +
  labs(
    title = "Actual vs Predicted with Regression Line (20% random split)",
    x = "Actual Outage",
    y = "Predicted Outage",
    color = "Legend"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Using `size` aesthetic for lines was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.

test_event <- c("idalia")  # for testing

train_data <- data %>%
  filter(!event_name %in% test_event)
  

test_data <- data %>%
  filter(event_name %in% test_event)

  mtry = c(4, 6, 8, 10, 12)
)

  x = train_data[, selected_vars],
  y = train_data$total_outage,
  method = "rf",
  tuneGrid = tune_grid,
  trControl = ctrl,
  ntree = 500,
  importance = TRUE,
  metric = "RMSE"
)
# View
